  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Federico Boccaccini's <em>Lotze et son h\u00e9ritage</em> (Peter Lang Verlag, 2015) is a specialist philosophical monograph dedicated to the thought of Hermann Lotze and his intellectual legacy. Published in the bilingual <em>Philosophie et Politique / Philosophy and Politics</em> series, the book has accumulated four citations across a decade, placing it in approximately the 73rd percentile for works of its type \u2014 a modest but meaningful foothold in an active niche of nineteenth-century philosophy scholarship. Its citing audience spans Germany, France, and Chile, reflecting the genuinely international reach of Lotze studies.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Boccaccini's contribution sits within a long-running Peter Lang series that brings together works on philosophy and politics with a consistently European orientation. The volume's placement in that series signals its ambition to situate Lotze's thought within broader intellectual and political traditions rather than treating him as a narrowly historicist curiosity. The book is commercially available through major retail channels and holds library copies in at least four institutions catalogued through WorldCat \u2014 a baseline level of physical accessibility that matters for specialist monographs on nineteenth-century German philosophy, where the reading community is concentrated but attentive.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The citation record, though numerically small, is notably durable and geographically dispersed. A first citation appeared in 2017, followed by uptake in 2021, 2022, and most recently 2025, indicating that the book continues to be encountered and found useful rather than having been absorbed and forgotten early in its life. The citing works span two journal articles and two book chapters: Nikolay Milkov at Paderborn University engaged with it in a study of Lotze's philosophy of psychology published in the <em>Klassische Texte der Wissenschaft</em> series; Charlotte Morel drew on it in <em>Les Cahiers philosophiques de Strasbourg</em> in work on reconciling idealism and realism after Hegel; and Jacinto P\u00e1ez Bonifaci at Universidad Diego Portales cited it as recently as 2025 in <em>Anuario Filos\u00f3fico</em> on objectification and validity in Lotze's theoretical philosophy. Each citation addresses a genuinely distinct philosophical question, suggesting that the book functions as a foundational reference across several sub-debates rather than serving a single specialized argument.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The thematic range of the citing literature \u2014 touching on philosophy of psychology, post-Hegelian metaphysics, and epistemology \u2014 reflects the breadth of Lotze's own influence, which extended from German Neo-Kantianism through to early analytic philosophy. Boccaccini's study appears to be serving as a point of orientation for scholars working across these downstream traditions. The geographic spread of citing institutions (Germany, France, Chile) further underscores that interest in Lotze's heritage is not confined to the German-speaking world but has taken hold in Francophone and Latin American philosophical communities, precisely the multilingual readership the Peter Lang series is positioned to reach.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, <em>Lotze et son h\u00e9ritage</em> occupies a credible and sustained position within a specialist scholarly conversation. For a monograph on a nineteenth-century philosopher published in a discipline where citation counts are structurally lower than in the sciences, its citation trajectory \u2014 spread evenly across eight years and three continents \u2014 reflects the kind of quiet, durable scholarly utility that defines a reliable reference work in the history of philosophy.</p>",
